South Africa Police Services (SAPS) officers stop looters from looting in central Durban, on July 11, 2021. AFP JOHANNESBURG - Police had insufficient capacity to curb the violence and the size of the crowds made it impossible to stop the looting. These are some of the key findings detailed in the expert panel report on the July 2021 unrest. President Cyril Ramaphosa gave the green light for its release on Monday. READ: Ramaphosa authorises release of report into July 2021 unrest The violence started in Kwazulu-Natal and later spread to parts of Gauteng. Experts concluded the police's response was ineffective. Police Minister Bheki Cele sought to justify this in his submission saying the suspension of six officers weakened the crime intelligence division.